President Barack Obama has declared September 2011 as National Alcohol and Drug Addiction Recovery Month. In his proclamation, he emphasizes the importance of promoting recovery and supporting individuals and families struggling with substance abuse. The President acknowledges the challenges faced by those in recovery and highlights the need to dispel myths and stigmas surrounding addiction. He also mentions the threat posed by alcohol and drug abuse, including the epidemic levels of prescription medication abuse and the dangers of drunk and drugged driving. The President expresses his commitment to reducing substance abuse through various measures, including research, education, increased access to treatment, and community-based recovery support. He calls upon the people of the United States to observe this month with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities to raise awareness and celebrate the transformative power of recovery.